    <div class="tips">
        <h1>Avalanche Safety Tips</h1>
    
        <p>Avalanches are possible any time there is snow on a slope. Check the forecast before heading into the mountains.</p>
    
        <h2>When There Isn't a Current Avalanche Forecast:</h2>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>1. Slope Inclination:</strong> Avalanches are possible on slopes steeper than 30 degrees.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>2. Timing:</strong> Most avalanches happen during snowstorms, strong winds, or thaws.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>3. Signs of Higher Avalanche Danger:</strong> Watch for recent avalanches, cracking, or audible collapsing. Avoid similar slopes.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>4. Safety Gear:</strong> Always ski with a friend and carry beacons, shovels, and probes for emergencies.</p>
        </div>
    
        <h2>Avalanche Types:</h2>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>1. Loose Dry:</strong> Release of dry, unconsolidated snow. Usually harmless but avoid terrain traps.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>2. Storm Slab:</strong> Release of a soft cohesive layer of new snow. Be cautious in steep terrain with traps.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>3. Loose Wet:</strong> Release of wet unconsolidated snow or slush. Move to colder, shadier slopes in the afternoon.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>4. Wet Slab:</strong> Release of a cohesive layer of moist or wet snow. Avoid terrain with suspected Wet Slab activity.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>5. Persistent Slab:</strong> Release of a cohesive layer in the middle to upper snowpack due to a persistent weak layer. Make conservative terrain choices. These are an ongoing problem hence the persistence.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>6. Deep Persistent Slab:</strong> Release of a thick cohesive layer deep in the snowpack. Very destructive and difficult to forecast.</p>
        </div>
    
        <h2>American Avalanche Center Danger Ratings:</h2>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>1. Low:</strong> Generally safe avalanche conditions; watch for unstable snow on isolated terrain features.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>2. Moderate:</strong> Heightened avalanche conditions on specific terrain features; evaluate snow and terrain carefully.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>3. Considerable:</strong> Dangerous avalanche conditions; cautious route-finding and conservative decision-making essential.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>4. High:</strong> Very dangerous avalanche conditions; travel in avalanche terrain not recommended.</p>
        </div>
    
        <div class="list-item">
            <p><strong>5. Extreme:</strong> Avoid all avalanche terrain; large, deep, and very dangerous avalanches are likely.</p>
        </div>
    
        <p>Stay informed, be prepared, and prioritize safety in avalanche-prone areas.</p>
    </div>
    
